			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">CpxR evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>CpxR and CpxA showed 97 % and 96 % identity to the respective E. coli counterparts ( Danese & Silhavy , 1998 ; Dong et al. , 1993 ; McClelland et al. , 2001 ; Weber & Silverman , 1988 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523114" target="_blank">14523114</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because CpxR of K. Pneumoniae exhibits the highest level of homology to CpxR of S. enterica serovar Typhimurium ( 96 % ) , CpxR of S. enterica serovar Typhimurium may directly bind to the promoter region of acrD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27199934" target="_blank">27199934</a>]<br></li>
<li>The E. coli K12 CpxR is 97 % identical to that of S. Typhimurium 14028s ; thus , the plasmid pCA-CpxR from the ASKA library ( Kitagawa et al. , 2005 ) , which expresses the E. coli K12 CpxR from an IPTG-inducible promoter , was used in these assays .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26300871" target="_blank">26300871</a>]<br></li>
